"We know that some diseases are passed from parents to children. Sometimes they are passed from grandparents to grandchildren and skip the parent. Sometimes they skip more than one generation. We can observe this all across society and it has been consistent for hundreds of years. 

This is possible due to DNA. Children are born with very similar DNA to their parents. This is why children often look like their parents, they may have similar qualities such as height or eyesight. Similarly they may also have similar defects such genetic exposure to certain diseases." {0,8-10}

DNA can mutate, it can also be defective. When this DNA information is passed from parent to child its sometimes the case that these defects go with them. This can be evident at birth or it may show up later in life. {4,2}

Some simple examples of this would be eye colour and blood group. We can see this in life. When one of both parents have for example a striking eye colour such as bright blue or silver blue this is often passed down to the child. This is where DNA works well, by passing down high quality traits. We can say the same for negative qualities that can be passed down. Such as a rare blood type or heart disease. {7}

It can also be difficult to tell what was passed down through DNA, what is a lifestyle factor and what is environmental. DNA is susceptible to mutations throughout life. This can be partly due to genetic susceptibility to mutation or due to something that happens or something we do, such as smoking. {13}
